    Daniel Perez3 months ago on Google
    1/5
    The biggest disappointment in my entire life. The place has lost all of its charm. I wonder how they give stars in Morocco but it does not deserve five AT ALL.
    To begin with, the room was not clean, there were rest of cookies everywhere, …
    The biggest disappointment in my entire life. The place has lost all of its charm. I wonder how they give stars in Morocco but it does not deserve five AT ALL.
    To begin with, the room was not clean, there were rest of cookies everywhere, bedlinen not changed, or flushed the toilet. They cleaned it in front of our very eyes when the concierge opened the door. Five minutes waiting to then have a room with a wet floor.
    Eventually we had to ask to be changed to another room because the one we got was connected to another one occupied by a noisy family. When we went to the reception, we were told that no other room was available, until I threatened to check out and take the next boat to Spain. Then suddenly there was a room available. It really is exhausting having to put up with such poor service and having to get mad to get something done.
    The rooms used to have beautiful wooden floors and windows, now they have been “modernised” with the cheapest materials. The tv had poor signal and so had the wifi.
    We tried to put on with the situation and went to the pool. This used to be an oasis in the middle of the city. Now it was turned into a WASTELAND, all filled with dirt that was not collected until the morning after. The water in the pool was not clear and no towels were available. A HUGE SPEAKER was playing DESPACITO.
    In other times you could have candlelight dinner with soft French music, now there are huge screen in the restaurant projecting soccer. We just left.
    The morning after, at breakfast, we were not even greeted or offered a coffee. Find a table by ourselves and go get coffee from the machine.
    There were plates piling up from the previous day.
    The entire place is filled with arrows and sun-bleached covid indications that are outdated and nobody ever follows, anyway.
    I’m so disappointed because I used to love this hotel, it reminded me to the times of the international Tangiers and it has been completely ruined by the current management. It’s so shameful and poor culturally speaking, it hurts.
    This is not a five star hotel, but rather a two or three. Do not pay for Minzah and go to any other hotel in Tangiers because you’ll get the same for less money.

    Kenneth Tangerois3 Maroc8 months ago on Google
    4/5
    El Minzah Hotel is one of the oldest and arguably the most famous luxury hotel in Tangier. It opened in 1930 and is centrally located downtown near the Place de France. It was expanded and transformed into a hotel after a casino (opened in …
    El Minzah Hotel is one of the oldest and arguably the most famous luxury hotel in Tangier. It opened in 1930 and is centrally located downtown near the Place de France. It was expanded and transformed into a hotel after a casino (opened in 1925) permanently closed.
    There are beautiful gardens with ocean views, spread around a large outdoor swimming pool, and there is a covered outdoor dining terrace, a large Moroccan restaurant, intimate Wine Bar restaurant and the elegant Caid's Bar with an occasional pianist.
    During the warmer months, the large inner courtyard is used for breakfasts and occasional exhibitions of art.
    There is a separate Wellness Center with small indoor pool, a spa, massages, gym, hammam, jacuzzi, women’s hair salon and men’s coiffeur.
    All of the rooms and suites facing the Rue de la Liberté have soundproof windows which are necessary due to the constant street noises. I would request a room or suite with a private covered terrace facing the pool or Mediterranean, the Strait of Gibraltar, the coast of Spain and that country's southernmost town of Tarifa.
    In late-March 2018, El Minzah Hotel closed for about six months while its interior rooms were upgraded and renovated. The hotel reopened in November 2020 during the coronavirus crisis, but there are a few guests.
    In March 2021, I visited a friend's business associate who stayed one week in a beautiful two-room suite with a comfortable sitting room, two telephones, two televisions, thermostat heating and air-conditioning controls for each room, a large walk-in closet and dressing room and a huge bathroom with floor to ceiling marble walls, marble floors and a marble sink. While there was no bath tub, the six-foot square glass-enclosed shower was impressive.
    The suite had views of the gardens below and the ocean in the distance from its 25-foot long covered terrace with arches, furnished with a comfortable sofa, a round table and several chairs.
    Hopefully this five-star luxury hotel will have many tourists the summer of 2022 since the airplane flights have resumed.
    Unfortunately the FRS ferries from Tarifa and Algeciras, Spain have still not resumed after over two years. Without a doubt, many Moroccan hotels (including El Minzah Hôtel) and innumerable businesses in Tangier and elsewhere in Morocco have lost tourist income and many are in dire straits financially.
    And who can bring their car on an airplane? Obviously, the ferry boats from Spain must reopen for the tourists as well as the annual summer Marhaba when many tens of thousands of Moroccans living and working in various European countries return to their native country to visit their Moroccan families while spending money in Morocco.
    They often bring their cars, and nearly all travel through Algeciras and Tarifa, not Sete, France or some out of the way port in Portugal.
    El Minzah Hôtel is an oasis of tranquility with Old World charm in downtown Tangier.

    Let's tick the basic boxes first. This place is centrally located. You'll be 30 seconds walking from a 24h minimart, 1 minute from a sushi place, 3 minutes from the beach, 5 minutes from the Casino. And so on...
    The staff is superb. I've seen places with more formal staff which were also pleasant, but down there the whole idea seemed to be: make them feel at ease, so they'll feel at home. My plan was t spend a night in Punta del Este before heading north but I just no showed on my other reservations because this city just attracted me like few places I've traveled to.
    Now, perhaps the hostel helped along this process by making me feel at home, but make a note that Punta del Este is a truly great place and may blossom to you if you give it a chance.
    The hostel has two floors and I stayed near the bathrooms on the first floor. The room, as well as the rest of the place, were meticulously cleaned by a lady every couple of days. The toilets were clean as well but some guests failed to sweep the floor after showering so it was wet sometimes. This is not the hostel's fault and I'm saying this to ask you, reader: don't be the one who disregards everyone else. You are not special and nobody cares about you.
    The room had AC and heating. I had to turn on the heater because it was getting quite cold at night and it worked perfectly. The room was very warm and cozy all night long.
    There was a computer at the reception which seemed to be for the use of guests but it was out of service when I was there. The Wi-Fi connection is free and VERY GOOD. Excellent speed and strong signal even outside the hostel on the street, which will be useful if you want some privacy to make a Skype Call or something of that sort.
    They had a place to store my bicycle, which I took with myself to Punta del Este and there was no fuss about it. No extra fees and no hassle. Again, the staff really shines as one of the greatest aspects of this peculiar hostel.
    I paid USD 18 for each night during April. Low season. Some people thought it was expensive but I believe it was worth it. No doubt about it.
    Breakfast was coffee, tea, bread, some jams, orange juice, milk and cereals. I liked it because it was available until 10h30m.
    I really recommend this place if you're looking for a laid back original experience. If you are a stuck up person or couple or group who will get there and play your own little game in your own little world, then it makes no difference where you'll be. It will all be boring because, after all, the boredom is radiating from yourself.
    Smile and let this friendly place welcome you into one of the most peaceful places this time of the year.
    Room Tip: You might ask for rooms on the second floor if you want to avoid the noise from the common areas

    About this hotel

    This refined hotel in a stately building dating from 1930 is 15 minutes' walk from Municipale Beach and the Strait of Gibraltar, and 3 km from Tanger Ville train station. …

    Elegant rooms with artwork feature complimentary Wi-Fi, flat-screen TVs and minifridges; some offer strait views and/or ornate furnishings. Upgraded rooms have balconies; suites include living areas, sofabeds and/or whirlpool tubs.

    Parking is free. There are 2 restaurants, plus a wine bar and a piano bar. Other amenities consist of an outdoor pool and a sundeck, as well as a health club offering a sauna, a hammam and spa treatments. Fitness classes are available.
